      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(voyage): bound embedding-batch status and error reads",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nIn `extensions/voyage/embedding-batch.ts`, two external reads went through `withRemoteHttpResponse` unbounded: `fetchVoyageBatchStatus` (`await res.json()`) and `readVoyageBatchError` (`await res.text()`). Voyage batch responses are external provider content; a hostile or misconfigured endpoint can stream an arbitrarily large status JSON or error file that is fully buffered into memory — a memory-pressure / hang (OOM) vector on the batch worker. (The submit path already bounds its body via `postJsonWithRetry` → `post-json.ts`; only these two reads were unbounded.)\n\n## Evidence\n\nBoth reads now go through the shared bounded readers (`readProviderJsonResponse` / `readResponseWithLimit`, 16 MiB cap, cancels the stream on overflow) — same pattern as the recently merged #95218 / #96027 / #96038. Plugin-scoped. The status path throws on overflow; the **error-file** path **fail-softs by design** — an oversized error body degrades to `formatUnavailableBatchError` (cap value included so truncation is visible) rather than crashing the worker, and the normal NDJSON `trim/split/JSON.parse/extractBatchErrorMessage` chain and empty-file branch are preserved unchanged.\n\nReal behavior proof (live vitest, not mocked): real `ReadableStream` tests for status overflow (throws + cancel) and error-file overflow (fail-soft + cancel), plus regression tests proving the under-cap NDJSON parse chain and empty-file branch are byte-for-byte preserved.\n\n```\nTests  6 passed (6)\n```\n",
